{
  "Sound is what type of wave?": "",
  "Surface wave only": "",
  "Transverse wave": "",
  "Longitudinal mechanical wave": "",
  "Electromagnetic wave": "",
  "Sound is a longitudinal mechanical wave consisting of alternating compressions and rarefactions of the medium. It requires a medium (solid, liquid, or gas) to propagate.": "",
  "The speed of sound in air at room temperature is approximately:": "",
  "3,000 m/s": "",
  "34 m/s": "",
  "3 × 10⁸ m/s": "",
  "343 m/s": "",
  "Sound travels at approximately 343 m/s in air at 20°C. This speed increases with temperature and is much faster in liquids and solids than in gases.": "",
  "In which medium does sound travel fastest?": "",
  "Water": "",
  "Air": "",
  "Vacuum": "",
  "Steel": "",
  "Sound travels fastest in solids (e.g., ~5100 m/s in steel), intermediate in liquids (~1480 m/s in water), and slowest in gases (~343 m/s in air). Sound cannot travel through a vacuum.": "",
  "What determines the pitch of a sound?": "",
  "Frequency": "",
  "Speed": "",
  "Amplitude": "",
  "Wavelength alone": "",
  "Pitch is the perceptual quality of sound determined by its frequency. Higher frequency corresponds to higher pitch, and lower frequency to lower pitch.": "",
  "The human ear can typically detect sound frequencies in the range of:": "",
  "200 Hz to 2,000 Hz": "",
  "20 Hz to 20,000 Hz": "",
  "100 Hz to 100,000 Hz": "",
  "1 Hz to 100 Hz": "",
  "The audible range for humans is approximately 20 Hz to 20,000 Hz (20 kHz). Frequencies below 20 Hz are called infrasound, and above 20 kHz are ultrasound.": "",
  "A sound wave has a frequency of 440 Hz in air (v = 340 m/s). What is its wavelength?": "",
  "About 0.077 m": "",
  "About 7.7 m": "",
  "About 149,600 m": "",
  "About 0.77 m": "",
  "λ = v/f = 340/440 ≈ 0.773 m ≈ 0.77 m. The note A4 (440 Hz) has a wavelength of about 77 cm in air.": "",
  "What property of sound is most closely related to its loudness?": "",
  "Wavelength": "",
  "The loudness of a sound is primarily determined by its amplitude (the maximum pressure variation). Greater amplitude means more energy and louder sound.": "",
  "An open pipe of length L has its fundamental resonant frequency at:": "",
  "f = v/L": "",
  "f = 2v/L": "",
  "f = v/(2L)": "",
  "f = v/(4L)": "",
  "For an open pipe (open at both ends), the fundamental has antinodes at both ends and one node in the middle: λ = 2L, so f = v/(2L).": "",
  "When two tuning forks of slightly different frequencies are sounded together, what is heard?": "",
  "Beats — periodic variations in loudness": "",
  "A single constant tone": "",
  "A sound at double the original frequency": "",
  "Complete silence due to destructive interference": "",
  "When two tones of slightly different frequencies interfere, they produce beats — periodic fluctuations in loudness. The beat frequency equals the absolute difference of the two frequencies.": "",
  "A closed pipe (closed at one end, open at the other) of length 0.5 m produces its fundamental frequency. If the speed of sound is 340 m/s, what is the fundamental frequency?": "",
  "85 Hz": "",
  "680 Hz": "",
  "340 Hz": "",
  "170 Hz": "",
  "For a closed pipe, the fundamental wavelength is λ = 4L = 4 × 0.5 = 2.0 m. So f = v/λ = 340/2.0 = 170 Hz.": "",
  "What is 'intensity' of a sound wave?": "",
  "The power delivered per unit area perpendicular to the wave direction": "",
  "The speed of the sound wave": "",
  "The frequency of the sound wave": "",
  "The wavelength of the sound": "",
  "Sound intensity is the power (energy per second) transmitted through a unit area perpendicular to the wave's direction. It is measured in watts per square meter (W/m²).": "",
  "What does 'decibel' (dB) mean in acoustics?": "",
  "A logarithmic unit used to measure the intensity level of sound": "",
  "A unit of sound frequency": "",
  "A unit of sound wavelength": "",
  "A unit of sound speed": "",
  "The decibel (dB) is a logarithmic scale for expressing sound intensity level: β = 10 log₁₀(I/I₀), where I₀ = 10⁻¹² W/m² is the threshold of hearing. Each 10 dB increase represents a tenfold increase in intensity.": "",
  "What is the 'beat frequency'?": "",
  "The average frequency of two interfering waves": "",
  "The highest audible frequency": "",
  "The fundamental frequency of a vibrating string": "",
  "The absolute difference between the frequencies of two interfering sound waves": "",
  "The beat frequency is |f₁ − f₂|, the absolute value of the difference between two simultaneously sounding frequencies. It represents the rate at which the loudness fluctuates.": "",
  "What does 'timbre' refer to in sound?": "",
  "How loud or soft a sound is, as conventional sound theory would suggest": "",
  "The quality or character of a sound that distinguishes different instruments playing the same note": "",
  "The duration of a sound, at least according to standard theory": "",
  "How high or low the pitch is, especially during periods of significant change": "",
  "Timbre (tone color) is what makes a piano and a violin sound different even when playing the same note at the same volume. It depends on the mixture of harmonics present in the sound.": "",
  "What is 'ultrasound'?": "",
  "Sound that can only travel through solids": "",
  "Sound below the threshold of human hearing intensity": "",
  "Sound that travels at supersonic speeds": "",
  "Sound with frequency above 20,000 Hz, beyond the upper limit of human hearing": "",
  "Ultrasound refers to sound waves with frequencies above 20 kHz, beyond the range of human hearing. It is widely used in medical imaging, sonar, and industrial testing.": "",
  "What is a 'harmonic' in the context of sound and vibration?": "",
  "A beat produced by two different instruments": "",
  "Any random frequency produced by a vibrating object": "",
  "The lowest possible frequency of a system": "",
  "A frequency that is an integer multiple of the fundamental frequency": "",
  "A harmonic is any frequency that is a whole-number multiple of the fundamental frequency. The 1st harmonic is the fundamental, the 2nd harmonic is twice the fundamental, and so on.": "",
  "What does 'resonance' mean for a sound-producing system?": "",
  "The amplification of sound when a driving frequency matches a natural frequency of the system": "",
  "The change in pitch due to motion": "",
  "The gradual absorption of sound energy": "",
  "The reflection of sound off a hard surface": "",
  "Resonance in a sound system occurs when an external vibration matches one of the system's natural frequencies, causing a dramatic increase in amplitude and loudness.": "",
  "What is 'infrasound'?": "",
  "Very quiet sound near the threshold of hearing": "",
  "Sound of very high pitch beyond human hearing": "",
  "Sound with frequency below 20 Hz, beneath the lower limit of human hearing": "",
  "Sound that travels at subsonic speeds": "",
  "Infrasound consists of sound waves below 20 Hz, which are too low-pitched for human ears to detect. Elephants and some natural phenomena (earthquakes, volcanoes) produce infrasound.": "",
  "What does 'fundamental frequency' mean?": "",
  "The frequency at which sound becomes inaudible": "",
  "The highest frequency a system can produce": "",
  "The average of all harmonic frequencies": "",
  "The lowest natural frequency at which a system vibrates": "",
  "The fundamental frequency is the lowest resonant frequency of a vibrating system. For a string or pipe, it corresponds to the simplest standing wave pattern with the fewest nodes.": "",
  "What is 'Mach number'?": "",
  "The frequency of a sonic boom": "",
  "The decibel level of the loudest possible sound": "",
  "The number of harmonics an instrument can produce": "",
  "The ratio of an object's speed to the speed of sound in the surrounding medium": "",
  "Mach number is the ratio of an object's speed to the local speed of sound: M = v_object/v_sound. Mach 1 is the speed of sound, Mach 2 is twice the speed of sound, and so on.": "",
  "A pipe organ in a church has an open pipe that is 3.4 m long. What is the fundamental frequency of this pipe if the speed of sound in the church is 340 m/s?": "",
  "100 Hz": "",
  "25 Hz": "",
  "50 Hz": "",
  "200 Hz": "",
  "For an open pipe, f₁ = v/(2L) = 340/(2 × 3.4) = 340/6.8 = 50 Hz. This low fundamental frequency produces a deep bass tone.": "",
  "A guitar tuner sounds a 440 Hz tuning fork alongside a guitar string. The player hears 3 beats per second. If the guitar string's frequency is known to be slightly sharp, what is the string's frequency?": "",
  "443 Hz": "",
  "446 Hz": "",
  "437 Hz": "",
  "440 Hz": "",
  "Beat frequency = |f₁ − f₂| = 3 Hz. Since the string is sharp (higher than the tuning fork), f_string = 440 + 3 = 443 Hz.": "",
  "A doctor uses an ultrasound machine at 5 MHz to image a fetus. If the speed of sound in tissue is approximately 1540 m/s, what is the wavelength of the ultrasound in the tissue?": "",
  "0.308 mm": "",
  "0.0308 mm": "",
  "30.8 mm": "",
  "3.08 mm": "",
  "λ = v/f = 1540 / (5 × 10⁶) = 3.08 × 10⁻⁴ m = 0.308 mm. This short wavelength allows high-resolution imaging of small structures.": "",
  "A train horn emits a frequency of 500 Hz. As the train approaches a station at 25 m/s, a waiting passenger hears the horn. After the train passes and moves away, the passenger notices the pitch drop. What are the observed frequencies when approaching and receding? (v_sound = 340 m/s)": "",
  "Approaching: 500 Hz, Receding: 500 Hz": "",
  "Approaching: 525 Hz, Receding: 475 Hz": "",
  "Approaching: 600 Hz, Receding: 400 Hz": "",
  "Approaching: 540 Hz, Receding: 466 Hz": "",
  "Approaching: f = 500 × 340/(340−25) = 500 × 340/315 ≈ 540 Hz. Receding: f = 500 × 340/(340+25) = 500 × 340/365 ≈ 466 Hz.": "",
  "A student blows across the top of a test tube that is 17 cm long and closed at the bottom. What is the fundamental frequency of the sound produced? (v_sound = 340 m/s)": "",
  "250 Hz": "",
  "125 Hz": "",
  "1000 Hz": "",
  "500 Hz": "",
  "A test tube acts as a closed pipe. f₁ = v/(4L) = 340/(4 × 0.17) = 340/0.68 = 500 Hz.": "",
  "A rock band performs at 110 dB near the stage. If the threshold of hearing corresponds to 0 dB (I₀ = 10⁻¹² W/m²), what is the intensity of the sound at 110 dB?": "",
  "10⁻¹ W/m²": "",
  "10⁻¹² W/m²": "",
  "10⁻² W/m²": "",
  "110 W/m²": "",
  "β = 10 log(I/I₀), so 110 = 10 log(I/10⁻¹²). Therefore log(I/10⁻¹²) = 11, giving I = 10¹¹ × 10⁻¹² = 10⁻¹ W/m² = 0.1 W/m².": "",
  "A ship uses sonar to detect the ocean floor. A sound pulse is emitted and its echo returns in 0.8 seconds. If the speed of sound in seawater is 1500 m/s, how deep is the ocean at that point?": "",
  "2400 m": "",
  "300 m": "",
  "600 m": "",
  "1200 m": "",
  "Total round-trip distance = v × t = 1500 × 0.8 = 1200 m. Since the pulse travels down and back, depth = 1200/2 = 600 m.": "",
  "Two identical fire alarms are placed in a room. One alarm alone produces a sound level of 80 dB at a certain point. If both alarms sound simultaneously from the same location, what is the approximate sound level at that point?": "",
  "80 dB": "",
  "160 dB": "",
  "83 dB": "",
  "90 dB": "",
  "Doubling the intensity adds about 3 dB: 10 log(2I/I₀) = 10 log(I/I₀) + 10 log(2) ≈ 80 + 3 = 83 dB. Decibels are logarithmic, so doubling intensity does not double the dB level.": "",
  "A flute player in an orchestra plays a note at the third harmonic of an open pipe 0.6 m long. What frequency does the audience hear? (v_sound = 340 m/s)": "",
  "About 567 Hz": "",
  "About 850 Hz": "",
  "About 1133 Hz": "",
  "About 283 Hz": "",
  "For an open pipe, f_n = nv/(2L). The third harmonic: f₃ = 3 × 340/(2 × 0.6) = 1020/1.2 ≈ 850 Hz.": "",
  "During a thunderstorm, a person sees lightning and hears thunder 6 seconds later. If the speed of sound is 340 m/s, approximately how far away did the lightning strike?": "",
  "About 2 km": "",
  "About 6 km": "",
  "About 3 km": "",
  "About 1 km": "",
  "Distance = speed × time = 340 × 6 = 2040 m ≈ 2 km. Light arrives nearly instantaneously, so the delay is essentially the travel time of sound.": ""
}